---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import MetaFooter from "../components/MetaFooter.astro";
import BrandMark from "../components/BrandMark.astro";

const title = "What is Blink?";
const description =
  "Blink is a local-first Mac assistant for the replies hiding in plain sight: it reads your screen, drafts the next words, and stays quiet until you need it.";
---

<Base title={title} description={description} ogType="article">
  <main class="shell shell--scroll">
    <header class="row meta">
      <div class="cell">
        <BrandMark />
        <span>blink</span>
      </div>
      <div class="cell muted">story / 02</div>
      <div class="cell muted">essay</div>
      <div class="cell right"><a href="/">← back to index</a></div>
    </header>

    <section class="row article-row">
      <div class="cell article-cell">
        <article class="article">
          <h1>what is blink?</h1>

          <p>
            the slowest thing on my computer is me typing.
          </p>

          <p>
            a lot of what i put on the screen is just contextual continuation.
            the thread already implies the reply. the agent already gave me the
            answer. i'm not deciding, i'm transcribing, and by the end of the
            day i've typed thousands of words that any reasonable person in my
            seat would have typed the same way.
          </p>

          <p>
            so blink is built on a simple bet: most replies aren't original,
            and once a tool can see what you see, it can write them for you.
          </p>

          <p>
            the idea isn't new and the model isn't the hard part. the hard
            part is making it fast and quiet enough that you forget it's
            there.
          </p>

          <p>
            this hits hardest where the load is heaviest, which right now is
            anyone working with agents. every agent is a thread that wants a
            response, and the response is usually a function of context the
            agent just gave you. running four claude code sessions at once
            stops being a context-switching tax and starts feeling closer to
            piloting. four agents, one operator, almost no typing. that's the
            wedge.
          </p>

          <p>
            it doesn't stay there. the same loop fits most of what people do
            at a computer. email, messages, comments, reviews, posts. anywhere
            the reply is a function of what's already on screen, blink
            collapses it into a keystroke.
          </p>

          <p>
            what changes when this works is the texture of the day. the part
            that was just transcription disappears. the agent gets unblocked,
            the slack thread moves on without you, the x reply ships while
            you're already reading the next thing. you stop being the
            bottleneck on responses you'd already finished in your head, and
            your attention is free for the small number of things that
            actually require you.
          </p>

          <p>
            the future i'm building toward is one where your computer feels
            less like a thing you operate and more like a thing that operates
            with you. it watches what you're doing, knows how you'd respond,
            and stays out of the way until you decide. the words you would
            have typed are just there, ready. typing becomes the mode you
            switch into when you actually have something new to say.
          </p>

          <p>
            blink reads your screen and writes the rest. once you feel it,
            you won't go back.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <MetaFooter />
  </main>

  <style>
    .article-row {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      min-height: 0;
    }

    .article-cell {
      padding: clamp(48px, 7vh, 88px) clamp(28px, 5vw, 64px)
        clamp(64px, 9vh, 112px);
      align-items: flex-start;
      justify-content: center;
    }

    .article {
      width: 100%;
      max-width: 640px;
    }

    .article h1 {
      font-size: clamp(40px, 5.5vw, 64px);
      font-weight: 700;
      letter-spacing: -0.045em;
      line-height: 1;
      margin-bottom: 32px;
      color: var(--fg);
    }

    .article h2 {
      font-size: clamp(20px, 2vw, 24px);
      font-weight: 700;
      letter-spacing: -0.015em;
      line-height: 1.25;
      margin-top: 56px;
      margin-bottom: 16px;
      color: var(--fg);
    }

    .article p {
      font-size: clamp(16px, 1.3vw, 18px);
      line-height: 1.65;
      color: #2a2a2a;
      margin-bottom: 18px;
      text-wrap: pretty;
    }

    .article .lede {
      font-size: clamp(18px, 1.5vw, 21px);
      color: var(--fg);
      font-weight: 500;
      line-height: 1.55;
      margin-bottom: 28px;
    }

    .article a {
      border-bottom: 1px solid var(--fg);
    }

    .article a:hover {
      background: var(--accent-soft);
      color: var(--fg);
    }

    @media (max-width: 880px) {
      .article-cell {
        padding: 40px 20px 64px;
      }

      .article h2 {
        margin-top: 40px;
      }
    }
  </style>
</Base>
